10
00:00:52,200 --> 00:01:04,220
So, the first point will be the statement that the operating frequency of the Tesla transformer, in this case in kHz, will determine the length of its conductor.

11
00:01:04,980 --> 00:01:07,720
This was and will be, and it's unchanging.

12
00:01:08,020 --> 00:01:47,600
If in some videos you see that a person, for example, wound some Tesla transformer, wound an inductor arbitrarily on it, assembled such a system, connected it to a lab signal generator and is picking frequency on this inductor here and shows you on the oscillogram he has maximum sine amplitude — then this person doesn't know how a Tesla transformer is made.

13
00:01:48,550 --> 00:01:54,780
He in this case shows you the LC resonance frequency of this coil, no more than that.

14
00:01:55,540 --> 00:02:01,640
In exceptional cases the person may not even suspect this himself.

15
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:25,860
This coil may well work at that moment, that simply matched so that the length of all the conductor wound on this coil — at him by build matched wire diameter, frame diameter, winding height — that the LC resonance frequency is close to the frequency on conductor length.

16
00:02:26,820 --> 00:02:31,560
So this can personally lead the person to delusion.

17
00:02:32,380 --> 00:02:40,980
So if you saw such a moment in some video, put a million dislikes there, throw it with whatever you want.

18
00:02:40,980 --> 00:02:47,700
Joking of course, but the person will sometime come to a normal understanding themselves if they work.

19
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,440
How is this frequency determined?

20
00:02:55,620 --> 00:03:04,400
First its value will proceed from what elemental base we have to be able to work out this frequency in kHz.

21
00:03:04,940 --> 00:03:14,460
If, say, we work on spark gaps, then very well there turns out to drive such Tesla transformer to its resonance frequency.

22
00:03:15,920 --> 00:03:29,540
But if we work on semiconductor techniques, then we have significant limitations in operating frequency, and control electronics are also limited.

23
00:03:30,080 --> 00:03:40,660
So to start, if you'll do your first Tesla transformer, the recommended frequency is approximately in the range from 200 to 500 kHz.

24
00:03:41,220 --> 00:03:51,540
For this practically everything is available now, and I gave the schemes on my channel so such a Tesla transformer worked optimally.

25
00:03:52,760 --> 00:04:00,420
For example, I determined the frequency I'll work at — say I'll do at 200 kHz.

26
00:04:00,420 --> 00:04:04,060
For example, you can take any from 200 to 500.

27
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:12,620
Now we need to determine what wavelength we'll have for this frequency.

28
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:16,460
Say, we still haven't bought anything, no wire, no frame.

29
00:04:17,340 --> 00:04:21,020
This is now we have an equation with unknowns, and we determine.

30
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:38,040
Now I go to the online calculator that can count for us the wavelength for 200 kHz, or do this as I showed in my previous video about Tesla transformer calculation by conductor length.

31
00:04:38,860 --> 00:04:44,900
In this case I went to the online calculator on the site of radio amateurs of the Tula region.

32
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:45,760
Good site.

33
00:04:46,600 --> 00:04:57,220
And here is the online calculator that lets you calculate wavelength from its frequency or calculate frequency from a given length in meters.

34
00:04:57,220 --> 00:04:58,900
Let's calculate.

35
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:03,720
We determined that our frequency will be 200 kHz.

36
00:05:07,490 --> 00:05:09,870
And press calculate.

37
00:05:10,350 --> 00:05:12,170
We get 1500 m.

38
00:05:13,170 --> 00:05:18,710
200 kHz for us equals 1500 m.

39
00:05:19,110 --> 00:05:28,290
For us to get a quarter-wave resonator, we need this length of 1500 m divide by 4.

40
00:05:28,290 --> 00:05:36,410
And we get, if you divide, 375 m.

41
00:05:37,170 --> 00:05:44,930
So, we got the conductor length we should lay on our future frame.

42
00:05:45,110 --> 00:05:49,650
Now the time has come to determine the frame diameter.

43
00:05:50,930 --> 00:05:55,110
There are many plastic frames, including sewer pipes.

44
00:05:55,110 --> 00:06:01,410
The pipes available are diameters 110 mm, 75 mm, 50 mm.

45
00:06:03,550 --> 00:06:08,170
Let's calculate our coil for two common frames.

46
00:06:08,250 --> 00:06:11,770
110 mm and 75 mm accordingly.

47
00:06:12,450 --> 00:06:19,150
Whoever has cardboard frames, those will be the best frames, you can calculate for them.

48
00:06:19,250 --> 00:06:23,330
You need to accurately measure the diameter with calipers.

49
00:06:23,330 --> 00:06:26,130
For now we calculate for the 110 pipe.

50
00:06:26,610 --> 00:06:32,690
We determined the diameter is 110 mm.

51
00:06:34,030 --> 00:06:43,370
Now we need to find out the turn length that fits in one revolution on this 110 mm pipe.

52
00:06:43,470 --> 00:06:52,690
For this we use the standard formula from the school math course for determining circumference length.

53
00:06:52,690 --> 00:06:55,030
This formula looks like this.

54
00:06:55,170 --> 00:07:06,950
Circumference length equals the number π multiplied by diameter, where π for us is 3.14.

55
00:07:08,990 --> 00:07:11,890
Do the math calculations.

56
00:07:14,790 --> 00:07:23,610
3.14 multiplied by 0.11.

57
00:07:23,790 --> 00:07:26,330
I converted millimeters to meters.

58
00:07:32,110 --> 00:07:39,150
We get 0.345 m.

59
00:07:40,150 --> 00:07:47,970
Now we have the turn length for the 110 pipe.

60
00:07:48,570 --> 00:07:59,450
The next moment is we determine what turn count at this conductor length we'll have on the 110 pipe.

61
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:12,790
We take our 375 m and divide by the calculated turn length of 0.345.

62
00:08:14,210 --> 00:08:23,030
And we get that we have a turn count equal to 1087 pieces.

63
00:08:23,030 --> 00:08:29,810
The next stage is we determine what conductor we'll wind our coil with.

64
00:08:30,910 --> 00:08:35,610
I'll take for calculation a conductor that's common.

65
00:08:36,110 --> 00:08:41,670
Its diameter is 0.25 mm.

66
00:08:41,990 --> 00:08:44,150
This is the core diameter by copper.

67
00:08:44,950 --> 00:08:49,150
And by varnish it's 0.26 mm.

68
00:08:50,370 --> 00:08:53,610
Common and inexpensive wire.

69
00:08:53,990 --> 00:09:02,830
If you have wire bought in advance or any present, you enter its diameter here.

70
00:09:03,110 --> 00:09:07,630
